{
  "text": "Theorem 13 (Finite BDPs [CITATION_1] , [CITATION_2] ): The problem of deciding whether the supremum probability of extinction of a given population is ≥ p is in PSPACE. Deciding whether this value is 0, 1 or in between is in PTIME. Moreover, there always exists an optimal static and memoryless strategy that maximises the probability of extinction. c) Timed Branching Processes.: Let T be a TBP and T RA be its region abstraction. To map a state of a TBP to the corresponding state in the region graph we define the operator We show in Theorem 14 that the problem of computing the extinction probability of a TBP T can be reduced to the same problem for its corresponding region abstraction (a finite BDP). This reduction is simpler than showing this for the boundary region abstraction that we used for the expected total reward objective (for which this simpler region abstraction does not work). C. Time-Bounded Extinction Probability.",
  "correct_citation": {
